ments of the Anglo-American Common Law and the European Civil Law traditions. This new collection of essays compares key areas of private law in Scotland and Louisiana. In 13 chapters, written by distinguished scholars on both sides of the Atlantic, it explores not only legal rules but also the reasons for the rules, discussing legal history, social and cultural factors, and the law in practice, in order to account for patterns of similarity and difference. Contributions are drawn from the Law Schools of Tulane University, Louisiana State University, Loyola University New Orleans, the American University Washington DC, and the Universities of Aberdeen, Strathclyde and Edinburgh.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCivil lawzLouisiana. 0aCivil lawzScotland. 4aLaw. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh1 aChalmers, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHogg, Martin A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLovett, John A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacQueen, Hector L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacgregor, Laura J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNorrie, Kenneth McK., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPaisley, Roderick R. M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPalmer, Vernon Valentine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReid, Elspeth Christie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReid, Elspeth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aReid, Kenneth G. C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScalise, Ronald J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rela